                                                                                                               Trade pact with South Korea
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Commerce minister Anand Sharma (left) with South Korean trade minister Kim Jong-hoon in Seoul on Friday. (AP)				                                 
	New Delhi, Aug. 7: India and South Korea today signed the Comprehensive Economic Partnership Agreement (CEPA), which could benefit the formers automobile and consumer durables industries.        
	Under the pact, which is like a free trade agreement, the two countries will substantially lower import tariffs on car parts and electronic items over the next 10 years.         
	The agreement is expected to come into force early next year after it is ratified by the South Korean parliament.        
	The CEPA will eliminate or reduce duties on 85 per cent of Korean goods that India imports. Similarly 90 per cent of Indian goods exported to Korea will get duty benefits.        
	Rajiv Mitra, spokesperson for Hyundai Motors India, said, The agreement will help us to price our products more competitively in the long run. As of now, we have no clarity on the exact impact.        
	According to data available with the Automotive Component Manufacturers Association, India imported auto parts worth Rs 23,470 crore between April last year and January this year. Of this, the highest import was from Korea, amounting to Rs 4,295 crore. India mainly imports gear boxes, certain engine parts, bolts, nuts, drive axle and clutches from Korea.         
	During the same period, India exported components worth Rs 13,987 crore. Of this, goods worth Rs 328 crore were shipped to Korea. The durables sector, too, has welcomed the trade agreement.        
	The treaty will strengthen trade relations between the two countries and we welcome this initiative, said R. Zutshi, deputy managing director of Samsung India, which imports compressors from Korea for its refrigerators.        
	According to industry data, about 10-15 per cent of imported components required by the durables firms come from Korea.                                                                                                                                        
